President Joe Biden delivered a speech in the East Room of the White House to celebrate Eid and mark the end of the holy month of Ramadan. He welcomed representatives Tlaib and Carson, as well as Representative Omar, although she couldn't attend. Biden expressed his gratitude to Muslim frontline workers, first responders, and scientists who contributed to the fight against the pandemic. He acknowledged the bittersweet nature of the occasion due to the families who lost loved ones to COVID-19. Biden highlighted the importance of empathy, community, and inclusivity, and recognized the contributions of Muslim-Americans in various fields. He also emphasized the need to address challenges and threats faced by the Muslim community, such as targeted violence and Islamophobia. Biden reiterated his commitment to a more equitable and inclusive nation and expressed his pride in serving as President to the Muslim community. The speech concluded with blessings for America and its troops.